# brain2 — Hung's Second Brain Vault

This is a personal LLM-maintained knowledge wiki. Any LLM (Claude Code,
Codex, etc.) opened in this directory should follow the conventions
below. The companion skill that drives ingest/query/lint operations is
`~/.claude/skills/second-brain/`.

## Layout — two top-level areas

```
brain2/
├── CLAUDE.md              # this file — conventions for the vault
├── log.md                 # chronological activity log (append-only)
├── raw/                   # immutable source documents — never edit
│   ├── assets/            # images
│   └── notion/            # Notion exports preserved with their hash IDs
└── wiki/                  # LLM-curated knowledge — the compounding artifact
    ├── wiki.md            # vault router (folder-note)
    ├── overview.md        # identity — "who is Hung"
    ├── work/              # company/job knowledge — MoMo-specific lives here
    ├── code-knowledge/    # generic tech, transferable across jobs
    ├── projects/          # personal/side projects (when accreted)
    ├── research/          # active deep-dive research (when accreted)
    ├── doing/             # current focus / WIP / status (when accreted)
    └── personal/          # health, goals, journal (when accreted)
```

`brain2/` is the storage container with two piles: immutable `raw/`
sources on one side, LLM-curated `wiki/` on the other.

Inside each life-area folder, organize by **domain hierarchy**, not by
file type. Nest folders to mirror the real domain structure (e.g.
`work/momo/app-platform/load-miniapp/`). Every folder gets its own
folder-note MOC (same name as folder). Files within a folder are flat —
the page's `type:` frontmatter (`source` / `entity` / `concept` /
`synthesis` / `index`) distinguishes them.

**Per-folder MOC required (folder-note pattern).** Every folder has a
MOC file **named after the folder itself** — `work/work.md`,
`code-knowledge/code-knowledge.md`. This makes wikilinks clean and unique:
`[[work]]` resolves directly to the work MOC.

The MOC lists pages in the folder, groups into clusters, surfaces gaps.
Update on every ingest that adds/renames a page.

**No `## Parent` sections in folder notes.** Obsidian's Backlinks panel
handles upward navigation. Explicit parent wikilinks create bidirectional
arrows that clutter the graph.

Top-level navigation:
- `brain2/wiki/wiki.md` — vault entry point
- `brain2/wiki/overview.md` — identity page
- `brain2/wiki/<area>/<area>.md` — per-area MOC

**`work/` vs `code-knowledge/` — the key split:**

- `work/` = knowledge that only makes sense in the company's context
  (MaxAPI Core, BridgeMode 1/2, MoMo's bundle state machine).
- `code-knowledge/` = knowledge transferable to any job (Module Federation
  theory, Kotlin Coroutines, JSI, dynamic bundle injection as a pattern).

When in doubt, ask which side it belongs on.

## Hard rules

1. Never modify files in `raw/` once written — they're immutable record.
2. Never write outside `brain2/` — other HungVault folders (`Decisions/`,
   `Learning/`, `Projects/`, `Quick-notes/`, `Research/`, `my kanban.md`)
   are user-owned and outside this skill's scope.
3. One concept = one page — BUT gom into one page when multiple
   "concepts" describe the same thing in the same domain. User prefers
   coherent narratives over fragmented nodes.
4. English content (even though Hung converses in Vietnamese).
5. No emoji unless explicitly asked.
6. New life-area folders accrete as content arrives — don't pre-create.

## File naming

- All filenames kebab-case: `carl-jung.md`, `red-book-summary.md`.
- Slug = filename without `.md`. Display name in frontmatter `aliases:`.
- **Bare wikilinks only**: `[[carl-jung]]`, not `[[entities/carl-jung]]`.
  Obsidian resolves across the vault; folder paths are volatile.

## Frontmatter

Every wiki page starts with YAML frontmatter:

```yaml
---
type: source | entity | concept | synthesis | overview | index
created: YYYY-MM-DD
updated: YYYY-MM-DD
aliases:
  - Display Name
sources:                  # non-source pages — which sources back this
  - source-slug-1
tags: [topic1, topic2]
---
```

Source pages additionally:
```yaml
source_kind: article | book | paper | podcast | video | conversation | journal | image
source_path: raw/some-file.pdf
source_url: https://...
author: Name
date_published: YYYY-MM-DD
```

Synthesis pages additionally:
```yaml
question: "the question this synthesis answers"
```

Always update `updated:` when you edit.

## Wikilinks

- Internal: `[[page-slug]]` or `[[page-slug|Display Text]]` — bare slugs only.
- Citations: link to source pages, not raw files.
  E.g.: "Jung argued the unconscious has structure ([[red-book-summary]])."

## log.md

Append-only. Every entry: `## [YYYY-MM-DD] <op> | <title>`.

```markdown
## [2026-04-16] ingest | The Red Book by C.G. Jung
Created [[red-book-summary]]. Updated [[carl-jung]], [[individuation]].
Notable: introduced concept of [[shadow]].
```

Operations: `init`, `ingest`, `query`, `lint`, `manual`.

Grep recent: `grep "^## \[" log.md | tail -10`.

## On contradictions

New source contradicts existing claim? **Don't overwrite.** Add an
`## Open questions` or `## Contradictions` section to the affected
page citing both sides. Wiki should reflect the user's evolving view,
including unsettled parts.

## On compounding

Knowledge should compound. When a query takes real reasoning, file the
answer back as a synthesis page. Don't let explorations disappear into
chat history.

## Obsidian config

`.obsidian/app.json` has `userIgnoreFilters: ["brain2/raw/"]` so `raw/`
is hidden from Obsidian's file tree, search, and graph.

Recommended community plugin: **Folder Note Core** — clicking a folder
opens its folder-note automatically (matches our `<folder>/<folder>.md`
convention).

